Control Statements – C Programming
Introduction

Control statements in C are used to control the flow of execution of a program based on conditions and repetition. They help the program make decisions, repeat tasks, and handle different situations efficiently. These concepts are the core of logical programming and are used in almost every real-world application.

Mastering control statements builds a strong foundation for problem-solving, algorithm design, and advanced programming topics.

Topics Covered
if statement
if-else statement
else-if ladder
nested if
switch-case
for loop
while loop
do-while loop
break statement
continue statement

Problem Statements (11 Important Programs)

1) Check Even or Odd

Take an integer input and check whether it is even or odd using if-else.

2) Find Largest of Three Numbers

Input three numbers and determine the largest using nested if-else.

3) Simple Calculator (switch-case)

Perform arithmetic operations (+, -, *, /) using switch-case.

4) Grade Calculator

Input marks and display grade based on conditions:

90–100 → A
75–89 → B
50–74 → C
Below 50 → Fail
5) Vowel or Consonant Checker

Input a character and check whether it is a vowel or consonant using if-else.

6) Print Numbers from 1 to N

Use a loop (for or while) to print numbers from 1 to N.

7) Multiplication Table

Input a number and print its multiplication table using a loop.

8) Sum of First N Natural Numbers

Calculate sum of numbers from 1 to N using a loop.

9) Factorial of a Number

Find factorial of a given number using a loop.

10) Print Even Numbers from 1 to N

Use loop + condition to print only even numbers in a range.

11) Demonstrate Break and Continue

Print numbers from 1 to N:

Skip a specific number using continue
Stop loop at a specific number using break
